For each single terminal in the string we note the non-terminals that can produce it:

t40 → NT43  
t20 → NT9  
t76 → NT44  
t80 → NT53  
t91 → NT53, NT7  
t24 → NT59  
t29 → NT25

Hence the sets for the nine positions are  

1:{NT43}  2:{NT9}  3:{NT44}  4:{NT53}  5:{NT9}  
6:{NT53,NT7}  7:{NT59}  8:{NT9}  9:{NT25}

Now consider every binary rule in the grammar:

(NT30 NT53) (NT35 NT45) (NT53 NT11) (NT1 NT25) (NT59 NT5)
(NT15 NT1) (NT32 NT56) (NT44 NT33) (NT46 NT1) (NT1 NT4)
(NT62 NT7) (NT10 NT4) (NT43 NT16) (NT9 NT43)

For every adjacent pair of positions we look for one of these right-hand pairs:

positions 1-2 : (NT43 NT9) – not in the list  
positions 2-3 : (NT9 NT44) – not in the list  
positions 3-4 : (NT44 NT53) – not in the list  
positions 4-5 : (NT53 NT9) – not in the list  
positions 5-6 : (NT9 NT53)/(NT9 NT7) – not in the list  
positions 6-7 : (NT53 NT59)/(NT7 NT59) – not in the list  
positions 7-8 : (NT59 NT9) – not in the list  
positions 8-9 : (NT9 NT25) – not in the list  

Thus no substring of length 2 can be generated by any non-terminal.  
Without a non-terminal covering any length-2 substring, no longer substring can be built (every split of a longer span needs at least one length-2 piece). Consequently the start symbol S can never derive the whole nine-token string.

Therefore the given grammar does not generate the string.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:  

1. S → NT30 NT53  
2. S → NT35 NT45  

Therefore the first word of any string in the language must be the first word produced by NT30 or by NT35.

• NT30 has only terminal productions  
 NT30 → 't90' | 't53' | 't14' | 't27'  

• NT35 can begin with NT15 or NT1 (from NT35 → NT15 NT1 or NT35 → NT1 NT4).  
 – NT1 begins with 't89', 't10', or whatever NT10 derives, but never 't29'.  
 – NT15 can begin with 't12', 't38', 't76' (via NT44), or whatever NT1 derives, but never 't29'.

Hence, no derivation from either NT30 or NT35 can start with the terminal 't29'.  
Because the given string begins with 't29', it cannot be generated by this grammar.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT30 NT53  
   NT30 can produce only one of {t90, t53, t14, t27} as its first (and only) terminal, so any string it generates must begin with one of those four tokens.

2. S → NT35 NT45  
   NT35 can begin with NT15 or NT1. Tracing all possibilities for those non-terminals shows their first token can only be drawn from  
   {t12, t38, t89, t10, t73, t32, t76, t45, t53, t33}.  
   None of these is t80.

The given string starts with t80, which is impossible for either derivation path from S. Therefore the grammar cannot generate the provided string.
